<subSubSection pageId="69" pageNumber="70" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="69.[151,1437,796,1974]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,498,1515,1542]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Abdalla &amp; Mansell &amp; Sole" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Tjeder" baseAuthorityYear="1967" box="[506,730,1516,1542]" class="Insecta" family="Nemopteridae" genus="Afroptera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="segregata">
<emphasis box="[506,730,1516,1542]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Afroptera segregata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known from 
<collectingCountry box="[910,1054,1516,1542]" name="South Africa" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">South Africa</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1109,1205,1516,1542]" name="Namibia" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Namibia</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[1221,1319,1515,1542]" captionStart="FIGURES 151–152" captionStartId="70.[151,264,1888,1913]" captionTargetBox="[151,1285,179,1771]" captionTargetId="figure@70.[151,1285,179,1789]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="FIGURES 151–152. Distribution maps of Afroptera spp." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3335178/files/figure.png" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Fig. 151</figureCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry name="South Africa" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">South Africa</collectingCountry>
, the known range of distribution is from the Richtersveld Bioregion in the Succulent Karoo Biome (
<bibRefCitation author="Mucina, L. &amp; Rutherford, M. C." pageId="69" pageNumber="70" pagination="1 - 808" refId="ref48773" refString="Mucina, L. &amp; Rutherford, M. C. (2006) The vegetation of South Africa, Lesotho and Swaziland. In: Strelitzia. Vol. 19. South African National Biodiversity Institute, Pretoria, pp. 1 - 808." type="book chapter" year="2006">Mucina &amp; Rutherford 2006</bibRefCitation>
). The species seems to be associated with two different vegetation 
<typeStatus box="[1127,1190,1588,1614]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">types</typeStatus>
: the Central Richtersveld Mountain Shrubland where the area is montane with succulent shrubs and herbs, and characterised by mild winter rainfall with an average of 
<quantity box="[538,674,1659,1686]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="0.6" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" unit="mm" value="130.0" valueMax="200.0" valueMin="60.0">60–200 mm</quantity>
per year. The species is also associated with the Goariep Mountain Succulent Shrubland where the habitat comprises the Goariep Mountain (Ploegberg), vegetated mostly by dense succulent shrubs and 
<taxonomicName box="[393,444,1732,1758]" class="Liliopsida" family="Xanthorrhoeaceae" genus="Aloe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[393,444,1732,1758]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Aloe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and other 
<typeStatus box="[573,632,1732,1758]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">types</typeStatus>
of trees. The area receives winter rains with MAP 
<quantity box="[1208,1291,1732,1758]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" unit="mm" value="70.0">70 mm</quantity>
. In 
<collectingCountry box="[1333,1432,1732,1758]" name="Namibia" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Namibia</collectingCountry>
, the distribution is in the Kalahari xeric Savanna Ecoregion where the habitat is an open Savanna, known for its extreme aridity and poor nutrient sandy soils; vegetated mostly by grasses, 
<taxonomicName box="[962,1040,1804,1830]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Acacia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[962,1040,1804,1830]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Acacia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1093,1169,1804,1829]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Capparaceae" genus="Boscia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Capparales" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1093,1169,1804,1829]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Boscia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
trees. The area receives summer rains with an average of 
<quantity box="[526,675,1839,1866]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.25" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" unit="mm" value="325.0" valueMax="500.0" valueMin="150.0">150–500 mm</quantity>
per year (
<bibRefCitation author="Lovegrove, B." box="[788,977,1840,1866]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" refId="ref47910" refString="Lovegrove, B. (1993) The Living Deserts of Southern Africa. Fernwood Press, Vlaeber, 224 pp." type="book" year="1993">Lovegrove 1993</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Dennis, N. &amp; Knight, M. &amp; Joyce, P." box="[989,1199,1840,1866]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" refId="ref47444" refString="Dennis, N., Knight, M. &amp; Joyce, P. (1997) The Kalahari: Survival in a Thirstland Wilderness. Struik, Cape Town, 168 pp." type="book" year="1997">
Dennis 
<emphasis box="[1076,1125,1840,1866]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">et al</emphasis>
. 1997
</bibRefCitation>
). Another population was found confined to the extension of the Succulent Karoo Biome in southern 
<collectingCountry box="[1073,1172,1876,1902]" name="Namibia" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Namibia</collectingCountry>
, which falls within the Namaqualand-Namib Domain in southwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[686,782,1912,1938]" name="Namibia" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Namibia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Jurgens, N." box="[799,954,1912,1938]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" pagination="21 - 38" refId="ref47542" refString="Jurgens, N. (1991) A new approach to the Namib Region. Vegetation, 97 (1), 21 - 38." type="journal article" year="1991">Jürgens 1991</bibRefCitation>
). The area is characterised by winter rains and succulent vegetation.
</paragraph>
